Bernoulli and Binomial distribution
\[\mathcal{B}(n, p)\]
The binomial distribution represent the number of successes when performing n independent experiment having a constant probability of success p.
[It is a discrete distribution taking only positive integer values.{style=“font-size: 30px”}

It can be use for proportion: eg proportion of trees browsed in a plot.


The Bernoulli distribution is a special case of the binomial distribution where n=1.
It is a discrete distribution taking only the values 0 (failure) or 1 (success).]{style=“font-size: 30px”}


It can be use for presence/abscence and success/failure data: eg probability that a tree is browsed.]{.fragment}

